extends /views/templates/layouts/_base

append variables
	- pagetitle = "How it works"

block content
	.lane
		.container
			.page-header
				h1 How it works
				p.lead CSS can only transition between two real or relative values. Panel and PanelSet solve that.

	+section("The problem", "Problem")

		p It would be nice if CSS could transition the size of elements between closed (zero) and their natural size. Or have parent elements transition their size based on which child is visible. While there are already some advances in getting browsers ready to handle this (see the #[a(href="#faq") interpolate-size] question), it is not fully supported, and it also does not work in a generic way for all transitions. 
		
		p There are a few approaches that are commonly used now, each with tradeoffs:



	+section("Common approaches", "Approaches")

		.indented
			h3 Per-frame JavaScript

			h4 Drawbacks:
			ul
				li Sixty layout recalculations per second, or capped to less calculations, even worse. Stutter time. A nightmare on mobile. This is still used out there, probably because of standard tooling, Angular shizzle, whatever.

		.indented
			h3 The max-height hack
			p Pick a number (for example 2000px) that’s at least bigger than your content. The browser will transition the max-height. This is a pure CSS solution with no JavaScript.

			+codeblock('CSS').
				.panel {
					max-height: 0;
					overflow: hidden;
					transition: max-height 0.3s ease-in-out;
				}
				.panel.open {
					max-height: 2000px; /* I guess this will be larger than our content */
				}
			h4 Drawbacks:
			ul
				li Broken easing: the timing is counting towards the maximum size, not the actual content size. In the above example, the user will not see the '-out' part of the easing curve at all because the content has already stopped the growing.

		.indented
			h3 The CSS Grid workaround
			p Transition #[code grid-template-rows] between #[code 0fr] and #[code 1fr]. The inner element uses #[code overflow: hidden] to clip the collapsed state. This is quite a smart trick.
			+codeblock('CSS').
				.panel-outer {
					display: grid;
					grid-template-rows: 0fr; /* collapsed */
					transition: grid-template-rows 0.25s ease;
				}
				.panel-outer.open {
					grid-template-rows: 1fr; /* expanded */
				}
				.panel-outer > * {
					overflow: hidden;
				}
			p Used by: Material Design, many modern CSS-only implementations.
			h4 Drawbacks:
			ul
				li It only works from 0 to something for a single panel. No cross transitioning between panels.
				li The element needs to be assigned as a grid, even though it may not be a real grid. Grid is just used here because it accidentally results in the behaviour we are pursuing, not because the content calls for a grid layout. It’s a CSS hack.

	+section("The lock-measure-animate-unlock (LMAU) cycle", "LMAU")

		p Panel and PanelSet seem to be able to transition to or from a natural size, but they just use measurement to get explicit values. ‘Explicit’ sounds fancy, but it just means using real or relative values instead of #[code auto]. It is the same basic approach as used in for example react-collapse, but extended here to horizontal axes and panel switching. The sequence is the same for both:

		ol
			li
				strong Lock
				| : write the current dimension as an inline style. This gives CSS a concrete start value.
			li
				strong Measure
				| : make the target content briefly visible but absolutely positioned (so it does not affect flow), then read its offset dimension (#[code offsetHeight] or #[code offsetWidth]). This value is used in the next step.
			li
				strong Animate
				| : set the container’s inline style to the measured value inside a #[code requestAnimationFrame] call. The CSS #[code transition] runs between the locked start and the measured end.
			li
				strong Unlock
				| : once the transition ends, remove the inline style. The container is responsive again.

		+codeblock('JavaScript').
			// Simplified.

			// 1. Lock
			container.style.height = container.offsetHeight + 'px';

			// 2. Measure target (absolutely positioned, invisible)
			nextPanel.style.position = 'absolute';
			nextPanel.hidden = false;
			const targetHeight = nextPanel.offsetHeight;

			// 3. Animate
			requestAnimationFrame(() => {
				container.style.height = targetHeight + 'px';
			});

			// 4. Unlock after transition
			container.addEventListener('transitionend', () => {
				container.style.height = '';
				nextPanel.style.position = '';
			}, { once: true });

		br
		+anchor('h3')(title="What this enables")

		.grid-2
			.card
				h4 Expand and collapse
				p Any element from 0 (height or width) to its natural size, or back. The same as the Grid workaround, but with correct easing because the transition range matches the content range.

			.card
				h4 Panel switching
				p Switch between two panels that are both non-zero size. For example from a 200px panel to a 400px panel. The container animates smoothly between the values. In the mean time, transitions can be used for the inner panels.
		
		p CSS variables can be used to coordinate the container’s size change with the inner panels' content change. It just makes the developer’s life easier.


	+section("Unstyled by design", "Unstyled")

		p Most animation components come bundled with a design system: colours, borders, spacing, and component structure. Getting your own design in there means fighting the library’s CSS. #[em Kill the Chakra].

		.grid-2
			div
				h3 Component libraries
				+codeblock('CSS').
					/* You want this */
					.accordion { border-radius: 12px; }
					.accordion-trigger { background: none; text-align: left; }

					/* You get this instead */
					::ng-deep .mat-expansion-panel {
						border-radius: 12px !important; /* still doesn’t work */
					}
					::ng-deep .mat-expansion-panel-header {
						background: none !important;
					}
				ul
					li Opinionated design system
					li Specificity wars and #[code !important]
					li Styles break on library updates
					li Hard to use with Tailwind or CSS Modules

			div
				h3 Panel / PanelSet
				+codeblock('CSS').
					/* Zero CSS from the library */
					.accordion { border-radius: 12px; }
					.accordion-trigger { background: none; text-align: left; } /* just works */
				ul
					li No styling CSS included
					li No specificity conflicts
					li Works with Tailwind, CSS Modules, CSS-in-JS, anything
					li Your design system, not the library’s

	+section("FAQ (or: &nbsp;<em>Some remarks that people might have</em>)", "FAQ")
		.column.gap-1(data-panel-group data-panel-close-siblings)
			+faq("But you should use <code>interpolate-size: allow-keywords</code>")
				h3 It is used, but not all browsers support it
				p Both Panel and PanelSet use #[code interpolate-size: allow-keywords] as a “progressive enhancement” for opening and closing.

				p With #[code interpolate-size: allow-keywords], CSS can animate directly between #[code 0] and #[code height: auto]. If your browser supports that, then the #[u LOCK], #[u MEASURE] and #[u UNLOCK] steps from the LMAU cycle are simply skipped. That leaves the #[u ANIMATE] step. The JavaScript (yeah, it is still needed) detects support with #[code CSS.supports()] and then does far less: it just toggles state classes and listens to events. If your browser does not support it, it uses the normal JavaScript LMAU cycle.

				+codeblock('CSS').
					@supports (interpolate-size: allow-keywords) {
							[data-panelset].is-opening { height: auto; }
							[data-panelset].is-closing { height: 0; }
					}

				h3 Inner panel swapping
				p For the inner panel swapping of PanelSet, the JavaScript LMAU cycle is still needed. #[code interpolate-size] can animate between #[code 0] and #[code auto], but not between two non-zero #[code auto] values.

			+faq("But you should use <code>@view-transition</code>")
				h3 Yeah it was considered
				p View Transitions allows animating between different DOM states, and it can handle size changes. But VT wants to controle the whole visual transition in a before/after snapshot and can’t work with CSS variables. 
				p Maybe later when Level 2 element-scoped transitions mature and allow more control.


			+faq("But you say it is unstyled, and I still see styles")
				h3 Indeed there are styles
				p Those are just the documentation styles. Here is what Panel and PanelSet look like with nothing added:

				.grid-2.demo(stylee="background: white")
					div
						h3 Panel
						.raw-demo
							button(aria-controls="raw-panel") Toggle panel
							div#raw-panel(data-panel)
								.panel-wrapper
									+example-1(4)

					div
						h3 PanelSet
						.raw-demo
							.raw-demo-triggers
								button(aria-controls="raw-ps-panel-1") First
								button(aria-controls="raw-ps-panel-2") Second
								button(aria-controls="raw-ps-panel-3") Third
							+examplepanelset('raw-ps', false, 4)

	hr
	section.no-hr
		.container
			+anchor(title="Support this project")
			p PanelSet is free. If it saved you time, a coffee goes a long way.

			a.btn.solid.chevron(href="https://ko-fi.com/martinomagnifico" target="_blank" rel="noopener")
				+coffee()
				| Support my work on Ko-fi
				+chevron()




append scripts
	if isProd
		script(src=`${basePath}assets/scripts/example.js` vite-ignore)
		script(src=`${basePath}lib/panelset.js` vite-ignore)
		script.
			Panel.init();
			new PanelSet('#raw-ps');
	else
		script(type="module" src="/src/assets/scripts/example.js")
		script(type="module").
			import { Panel, PanelSet } from 'panelset';
			Panel.init();
			new PanelSet('#raw-ps');

append styles
	style.
		table.comparison {
			width: 100%;
			border-collapse: collapse;
			font-size: 0.9em;
		}
		table.comparison th,
		table.comparison td {
			padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
			text-align: left;
			border-bottom: 1px solid var(--doc-gray-200);
			vertical-align: top;
		}
		table.comparison thead th {
			border-bottom: 2px solid var(--doc-gray-200);
			font-weight: 600;
		}
		table.comparison tbody tr:last-child td {
			border-bottom: none;
		}
		table.comparison td:first-child {
			font-weight: 500;
		}